{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567536"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:03:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:03:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19115"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19115"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.3,0.1,0.06,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11849"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100893"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11849"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83318"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"5985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28183"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43722"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100893"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of severe pain, swelling, and redness of his right shoulder. He has a medical history of hypertension, osteoarthritis, and previous thyroidectomy for multinodular goitre. His regular medications include amlodipine, paracetamol, and thyroxine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. His right shoulder is warm, swollen, and tender with limited range of motion. Active and passive movement is limited by pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArthrocentesis is performed, yielding cloudy synovial fluid which is sent for microscopic examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following microscopic findings is most likely to be seen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Positively birefringent rhomboid crystals","Negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals","Positively birefringent needle-shaped crystals","Negatively birefringent rhomboid crystals","Non-birefringent cubic crystals"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an acute monoarthritis of the shoulder, which is a common site for calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease (CPPD/pseudogout). The patient\u0027s history of thyroidectomy is significant as thyroid disease is a known risk factor for CPPD. \u003Cstrong\u003EPositively birefringent rhomboid crystals\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of CPPD. These crystals appear blue when aligned parallel to the compensator and yellow when perpendicular under compensated polarised light microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENegatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of gout, caused by monosodium urate crystal deposition. Gout typically affects the first metatarsophalangeal joint, ankles, and knees, rather than the shoulder. The shoulder is more commonly affected by CPPD than by gout.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositively birefringent needle-shaped crystals\u003C/strong\u003E are not typically seen in joint fluid analysis. The birefringence suggests CPPD, but the morphology is incorrect as CPPD crystals are characteristically rhomboid or rectangular in shape.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENegatively birefringent rhomboid crystals\u003C/strong\u003E represent an incorrect combination. Rhomboid morphology is characteristic of CPPD, which are positively birefringent, not negatively birefringent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-birefringent cubic crystals\u003C/strong\u003E are not typically associated with any common crystal arthropathy. Basic calcium phosphate crystals can cause arthritis but are too small to be seen with light microscopy and require special staining techniques.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECrystal analysis using compensated polarised light microscopy remains the gold standard for diagnosing crystal arthropathies. The combination of crystal morphology and birefringence characteristics allows differentiation between gout and pseudogout. Other important synovial fluid parameters include cell count, culture, and glucose levels to help distinguish between inflammatory, infectious, and crystal-induced arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Positively birefringent rhomboid crystals are characteristic of pseudogout (calcium pyrophosphate crystals).","Calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease commonly affects the shoulder, knee, and wrist joints.","Thyroid disease is a known risk factor for calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease."],"references":["Pascart T, Liot\u00e9 F. Calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease. Lancet Rheumatol. 2024;6(3):e123\u2013e132. Available from: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanrhe/article/PIIS2665-9913(24)00122-X/fulltext","Firestein et al. Firestein \u0026 Kelley\u2019s Textbook of Rheumatology, 2-Volume Set, 12th Edition, 2024, ISBN 9780323935401","Dieppe PA, Swan AJ. Identification of crystals in synovial fluid. Ann Rheum Dis. 1999;58(5):261\u2013263. Available from: https://ard.bmj.com/content/58/5/261"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83318"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19115"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83318"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-27T22:26:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-27T22:27:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11849"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100893"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updated